<table border="0" width="570">
  <tr>
    <td>
<p ALIGN="CENTER">

<b></b><strong><font size="2">MATHEMATICAL ANALYSIS OF HEART RATE
VARIABILITY IN PRACTICE OF HIGH LEVEL SPORTS</font></strong></p>


<p ALIGN="CENTER"><font size="2">V.Nechaev, V.Konovalov, V.Gryaznov</font></p>

<p ALIGN="CENTER"><font size="2">Research Laboratory of AllRussian Academy of Physical
Culture, Moscow,<br>
Institute of Physical Culture, Omsk,<br>
Institute for Problems of Chemical Physics RAS, Chernogolovka, <br>
Russia</font></p>

<p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">Method of mathematical analysis of heart rate
variability is applied for estimation of physical state and correction of training process
in athletes specialized in long distance and marathon running and heel-and-toe walking.
Authors have many-year experience of using of this method in medical and training
practice. This experience shows on restrictions of standard method of analysis of heart
rate variability (Baevskii method) in cases of prevailing of slow waves of heart rate over
its respiration components. In these situations &quot;stress index&quot; of Baevski can
give results that are not so reliable as in opposite case (when amplitude of
&quot;fast&quot; respiration component of heart rhythm is much more than slow waves
amplitude). To remove this defect we propose &quot;modified stress index&quot;. To compute
its value numerical filtering is used for &quot;cleaning&quot; of original heart rate
record and removing low frequency components. Application of this method for estimation of
adaptation to training load of high level athletes is demonstrated.</font></p>
    </td>
  </tr>
